Edit: stole @jered&#39;s much better conditional instead of ternary

Classic use case for a [reducer][1]:

```
const arr = [ [1,2], [1,3], [1,5], [2,7], [3,0], [1,10] ];
const map = arr.reduce((acc, cur) =&gt; {
  return {
    ...acc,
    [cur[0]]: [...(acc[cur[0]] || []), cur[1]]
  };
}, {});

```

Of course, it could be a lot more readable than this... but [computed property names][2] and the [spread syntax][3] make it pretty slick and compact (it&#39;d fit on a single line if you wanted to).

Edit: ooo I like @woat&#39;s use of single character var names and [destructuring assignment][4] in the function signature :) We could throw that in too:

```
const arr = [ [1,2], [1,3], [1,5], [2,7], [3,0], [1,10] ];
const map = arr.reduce((a, [k, v]) =&gt; ({...a, [k]: [...(a[k] || []), v]}), {});

```

